│ Understanding the Issue: The SLP vectorizer is crashing with a memory       │
│ corruption error (malloc(): corrupted top size) during vectorization of a   │
│ loop containing PHI nodes and select instructions. The crash occurs in the  │
│ `processBuildVector` function when trying to vectorize a bundle of          │
│ instructions.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The log shows that the SLP       │
│ vectorizer is attempting to vectorize a bundle of 12 PHI nodes and then a   │
│ bundle of 12 select instructions. The cost analysis shows a negative cost   │
│ (-16), indicating vectorization is beneficial. However, the actual issue    │
│ appears when the vectorizer tries to process the build vector               │
│ operation.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: From the debugger inspection, I found │
│ that:\n   - `E->Scalars.size()` is 16 (the actual number of scalars in the  │
│ tree entry)\n   - `VF` (vector factor) is 12 (the intended vectorization    │
│ width)\n   - `GatheredScalars.size()` is 16\n   - `OrigScalarTy` is `i1`    │
│ (boolean type)\n   - The `GatheredScalars` array contains 12 valid FCmpInst │
│ values followed by 4 poison values of type `i1`\n   - `VecTy` is `<16 x     │
│ i1>` (a 16-element vector of i1)\n\nThe problem is in line 16250 of         │
│ `SLPVectorizer.cpp` in the `TryPackScalars` lambda function. The code       │
│ does:\n```cpp\nScalars.append(VF - Scalars.size(),                          │
│ PoisonValue::get(OrigScalarTy));\n```\n\nHowever, `Scalars.size()` is       │
│ already 16, and `VF` is 12, so this becomes `Scalars.append(12 - 16, ...)`  │
│ which is `Scalars.append(-4, ...)`. This causes undefined behavior because  │
│ `append` with a negative count can lead to memory corruption.\n\nThe issue  │
│ is that the code assumes `Scalars.size() <= VF`, but in this case, the tree │
│ entry has more scalars (16) than the vectorization factor (12). This can    │
│ happen when the SLP vectorizer creates tree entries with more elements than │
│ the current VF being considered.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n   + The    │
│ fix is to ensure we only append poison values when `VF > Scalars.size()`.   │
│ We should add a condition to prevent negative appends.\n\n5. Conclusion:    │
│ The fix prevents the memory corruption by ensuring that we only append      │
│ poison values when the vector factor is actually larger than the current    │
│ scalars size. This will prevent the negative append operation that causes   │
│ the malloc corruption."})                                                   │
